The architects saw - the office also includes a kindergarten
The office building Avriopoint in Brno is the new headquarters of the company Arch.Design.
But who would expect a mini garden here, with everything that belongs to it: colorful walls, creative furniture, a lot of toys and even a mini-parking on the outdoor terrace.
This kindergarten has been available to the employees of Arch.Design since last year.
The architecture and projection office Arch.Design, from which the Ateliers originate a whole series of renowned bronze buildings, calculated from the first designs for the new building Avriopoint with the premises for its company mini garden.
In a wise perspective, because most of his 90 employees are at the baby tree age and the company is interested in returning to their work as soon as possible.
Together with the possibility to work shortly, the kindergarten is another bonus that Arch.Design has to offer to its employees in the concept of its social programme.
The construction engineers have thus made it easier to put their demanding profession and child care under one hat.
The Minikindergarten is an original idea of the employees of Arch.Design and with the support of the management they managed to gain funding from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs for their project.
The operational mini-garden is financed by the Human Resources and Employment Policy Operations Programme from the European Social Fund and from the Czech Republic's State budget.
This funding (grants of CZK 2.8 million) enabled the necessary facilities and facilities to be purchased and for the duration of 2 years qualified staff and the operation provided.
After the use of the funding (2 years), the company Arch.Design is obliged to continue running the Minikindergarten for another 3 years at its own cost.
The preparation of this project took a whole year, with the company Economy Rating providing effective assistance in the application process.
The children take care of fully qualified staff - a nurse and a kindergarten teacher, the kindergarten can visit children without age restrictions, although most of them are over three years old.
And since this is a mini-kindergarten, only 5 children may be present at the same time, but the day varies over several children.
The kindergarten operation is flexible to suit the needs of parents, the children of all employees have the same rights in terms of the use of the kindergarten - without regard to the company hierarchy and their respective position.
Although it is individual education and care, the content of the programme in the mini-kindergarten is nevertheless comparable to the framework programme of pre-school education.
The children are not only playing here, especially they are offered excellent lessons - from basic knowledge to pre-school lessons, and they also learn English.
The classroom is not only equipped with toys and creative games, but also with a computer available to children.
What more - the presence of small children in the company contributes to a friendly and positive business environment.
The parents can take a look at the children at any time and thus avoid the stress when the children are taken late from a far away kindergarten.
The parents therefore use their working time more productive.
No wonder that there are also natural and loyal employer / employee relationships here.
Arch.Design thus enrolled among the Czech companies which offer significant benefits in recruiting new employees, which are family friendly and through such programs strengthen their personnel marketing.
A bone house also fascinates after 100 years. Look at the interiors of Gaudi
The roof mutates like the back of a prehistoric oak, the stairs like the spine of a dinosaurer and the balconies are ripped up fish mills.
This is the Casa Batlló of Catalan architect Antonio Gaudi in Barcelona.
Of the local inhabitants, the house with its organic forms received the nickname "Bone House."
Organic shapes, wild colors, the unusual use of stone, cachel fragments and mosaics, memorizing facades and all current soft lines, all these are typical features for the youth style of Antonio Gaudi.
The façade of the house plays with traumatic lines, delicate colors and textures that remind of nature and creatures.
Only when you look more closely, you notice that everything is dominated by geometry, rhythm and perception of order.
In the night, the whole facade is even more plastic, dramatic and the special illumination strengthens the shine of the colours.
The same vibrant lines and sloppy shapes also dominate the interior of the house.
Wavelshaped wood copies the window frames, rails, decorative elements of doors, even eye holes and bars.
The house Batlló in the district of Eixample on the lively shopping street Passeig de Grácia No. 43 was created by the conversion of a house from 1877, the architect Emilio Sala Cortese.
The reconstruction took two years and was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrial Josep Batlló, originally insisted on the demolition of the old and the construction of a completely new building, but ultimately he agreed to the idea of Gaudís for an unusual and also cheaper reconstruction.
The casa Batlló rental house, however, did not design Antoni Gaudí alone.
He worked with the architect Josep Maria Jujol.
The decorations for the representative apartment of the real estate owner and also the use of mosaics on the facade were created on its grid.
However, many other artists and artists also cooperated in the design of the facade.
The joint work on the designs for the Casa Batlló was the beginning of a fruitful cooperation between Jujola and Gaudí.
Thus Jujol also participated in the construction of Gaudís Haus Casa Milá in the Park Güell, where there are also other works of Antoni Gaudí.
Shortly after his completion, the house was given by the local residents of its organic forms because of the nickname "Bone House."
Others in turn called it the special window opening mechanism because of the "similar house."
It is also said that the sword of the Holy Georg, the Patron of Catalonia, is displayed at the top of the building.
But also other picturesque elements symbolize hidden religious motives.
Gaudí designed for the house a unique central heating system with ventilation channels and typical fireplace.
Something bizarre already mutates her 45-degree inclination.
In his work Gaudí consistently ignored all the construction regulations then and could not be misled by them.
Before the construction began, he collected the corresponding construction permit from the city, but the information he provided about the planned reconstruction was so vague that the city fathers were so discouraged two years later at the time of completion that they demanded remediation.
Among other things, the council rulers also insisted that the construction with its pillars even entered the public pedestrian.
However, there were no further amendments, on the contrary - only fifteen days after the urgency of the district, Josep Batlló submitted a request to authorise the rental of the two highest floors of the House - and it was promptly granted to him.
The house owner himself moved into the lower floors.
In the gallery on the 2nd floor there was a social salon, on the third floor there were the bedrooms and private rooms of the apartment.
The ground floor was parted to a jewelry store.
The entire six-storey building runs through a staircase up to the roof terrace.
All right angles and straight lines were removed by the basic elements of the conversion and replaced by curved and swung walls.
Gaudí also worked with a modern concept of interconnection of spaces.
The social part can be completely connected by opening the door doors and thus a larger society could easily talk without having to refrain from a certain degree of intimacy in more confidential conversations.
The house also received a rather unusual roof and two other floors by Gaudi's reconstruction except a new facade.
Also impressive is Gaudi's game with the light as well as the blue and white glazed hairs with which the courtyard is dressed and the lights.
The game of these two colors gives a maximum amount of light to all floors of the house.
At the same time he simply made the principle useful that white reflects the light better than dark colors that absorb the sunlight on the contrary.
The House Casa Batlló, which was included in the World Heritage List of Unesco in 2005, can visit everyone today.
The most spacious and spacious apartment is made available to the public on the first floor.
The house owners decided only in the year to take this step and this on the occasion of the 150.birthday of the famous Creator.
When it was found that this was a fairly beneficial business, the visits were maintained, yes they were also extended to other common and the roof floor rooms, including the roof terrace.
However, the price for visiting the monument is not a paperwork, it is 16.50 euros, students, pensioners, groups and owners of tourist cards receive 20 percent discount.
This amount exceeds the entry prices for other Gaudí buildings in the city.
Anyone who wants to get to know the real atmosphere of the house with his dragon towers should try to make friends with one of the residents and visit him at home.
