A longer Zeigefinger than ring finger means a lower risk of cancer
Men whose finger is longer than the ring finger are obviously at a lower risk of suffering from prostate cancer.
This is the surprising result of a study published on Wednesday by the British Journal of Cancer.
This is supposed to be related to the mirror of the male hormone testosterone.
"Our results show that the relative length of the fingers can serve as a simple test for the risk of prostate cancer, especially for men up to sixty," said the co-autorin of the study, Ros Eeles, professor at the cancer research institute at the University of Warwick.
The finger could help to determine which men should undergo a prostate cancer test, especially if genetic risks or other risk factors exist, such as family health burdens, Mrs Eeles added.
In the period 1994-2009, she followed with her colleagues in Britain more than 1500 patients with prostate cancer, but at the same time 3,000 healthy men.
With more than half of the participants in the study, the right hand drawing finger was shorter than the ring finger.
For these men, the probability of prostate cancer was the same as for 19 percent of those men whose ring and drawing fingers were equal.
However, in men whose finger was longer than the ring finger, this risk decreased by 33 per cent, and in men up to 60 per cent by 87 per cent.
The ratio of the length of the two fingers mentioned, which are already in prenatal age, clearly reflects the different levels of gender hormones that the child was exposed to in the womb.
Less testosterone corresponds to a longer pointer finger.
Previous research revealed that the testosterone is accelerating the growth of prostate cancer.
Václav Pačes, the leading Czech geneticist and former chairman of the Academy of Sciences, said ČTK that he was well known for this study, yet he does not consider the relationship between finger length and cancer risk to be "fully proven."
