Part of the debate on the present case is based on the fact that a team of the Real Madrid football club (who has presented in his hymne noble courage and honour and had punished his players for similar incidents on other occasions) played the main role, and on the dramatization by Mourinho, which has added an episode more to his long history as theatrical and provocative technicians.
In any case, the debate is about whether this behavior not expressly forbidden by the statutes contradicts the principles of sport, that is to say, whether these acts constitute a rule circumvention. In fact, this approach respects the statutes of sport, but seems to circumvent its sense.
In this case, the damage caused to the spirit of sport should be investigated.
The spirit of sport defends the physical integrity of the opponents, an aspect that was not endangered by these actions, because it was not an aggressive game.
Another aspect of a clean game is to avoid the violating players taking an unjustified benefit from the opposite team. Nor did that happen.
The paradox of the action of the players of Real Madrid is that it does not correspond to what we normally understand under wrong play or circumvention of rules, because the circumvention of the rule was not carried out secretly to avoid a sanction, but it should be as striking as possible so that it is punished by the arbitrator.
The players waited and took the sanction with pleasure.
Another question is what kind of advantage the contradictors have drawn from the deliberate fouls.
Here it should be emphasised that the rival was neither put in a more unfavourable position nor that benefits for the game played were raised, because the obvious result of this action was that the own team had to continue playing with fewer players.
It is also not a useful strategy for the next game, because the club does not have these players.
The advantage is obviously that players start the next season of the Champions League without cards that could threaten their participation in a future game.
But it is a long-term, up to a certain degree of unknown advantage, as the team could eventually exit. Furthermore, with this approach, players receive a sanction and pass into the second card cycle where they exit less because of card accumulation with a card than in the first cycle.
So it is not so clear whether this is really an advantage.
Finally, such practices are not directed against the spirit of sport, which also includes strategic decisions in order to make maximum use of the rules.
In this case, players did not want to circumvent sanctions (that would actually be a clear case of rule circumvention), they wanted to choose more when they undergo them.
They made a strategic decision without avoiding a punishment or escaping from it.
Although the limit between invention and the regulatory environment is wasted, I believe that this is a clear case of invention.
I have the impression that the polemics have arisen due to two factors: because it was two self-exclusions and because of the type of provoked regulation transfer.
The damage caused by these actions to the principles of sport is less ethical than rather aesthetic.
